Starting today, you can remix your friends‚Äô photos ‚Äî then send them back for fun conversations.

When viewing a photo message from a friend, tap the camera icon at the bottom and capture a reply. Your reply includes a sticker of what you‚Äôre replying to. Move and resize it, and add your own twist with stickers, text and drawings. You can remix photos back and forth for a fun visual of your conversation.

Additionally, you can now also control replays. Choose ‚ÄúOne View‚Äù for messages you want your friends to only see once. For everything else, choose ‚ÄúAllow Replay‚Äù so your friends have more time to view your messages. Photos and videos sent with ‚ÄúAllow Replay‚Äù loop automatically and your friends can tap and hold to pause.

New! Request to Join a Friend‚Äôs Live Video

Going live with a friend is now even easier. Starting today, when a friend is live, you can let them know you‚Äôd like to join in the fun and hang out live together.

When watching a friend‚Äôs live video, simply tap the ‚ÄúRequest‚Äù button in the comments section. You‚Äôll see a confirmation that your friend has accepted your request, and you‚Äôll have a moment to prepare. Once you‚Äôre live, the screen will split in half so you can hang out live with your friend. You can leave your friend‚Äôs live video at any time, making it easy to join for a quick hello or a longer chat.

When hosting your own live video, you can easily see requests from friends who want to join. In the comments section, you‚Äôll see a notification for each request. Just tap the ‚ÄúView‚Äù button and then choose to add your friend or cancel the request.

The new icon with two smiley faces will also have a red number showing how many requests you have. Tap the icon, and you‚Äôll see both requests and current viewers. You can either accept a request or invite a viewer to join you. 

As always, you can remove a guest and add someone else at any time. When you‚Äôre done, you can share your live video to stories, or choose ‚ÄúDiscard‚Äù and your live video will disappear from the app as usual. 

Going live together is the best way to connect in real time and have fun with friends, even when you‚Äôre not together. With this update, friends have even more ways to quickly join each other‚Äôs live videos.

To learn more about today‚Äôs updates, check out the Instagram Help Center: help.instagram.com/126662934757177

These updates are available as part of Instagram version 24 available for iOS in the Apple App Store and for Android in Google Play.

Weekend Hashtag Project: #WHPfindthelight

Light, camera, action! This weekend, the goal is to take photos and videos that showcase light in beautiful and diverse ways, as in this featured photo from Nadia (www.instagram.com/laporterouge). Here are some tips to get you started:

Light transforms ordinary scenes into extraordinary ones. Take a photo of the morning light as it pours into your kitchen, or during a sunset stroll. 

Have an outdoor portrait session with a friend. Try going during the golden hour, or find a perfectly and naturally illuminated wall to use as your backdrop.

Play with time and light together by photographing the same subject in the morning, afternoon and evening. Use multi-post to show how the light changes the scene throughout the day.

Today we‚Äôre introducing an interactive poll sticker in Instagram Stories that lets you ask a question and see results from your friends and followers as they vote. 

Whether you‚Äôre trying to plan tomorrow‚Äôs outfit, choosing which class to take or figuring out where to go for dinner, now it‚Äôs easy to share a two-option poll right in your story.  After you‚Äôve taken a photo or video for your story, select the ‚Äúpoll‚Äù sticker and place it anywhere you‚Äôd like ‚Äî you can write out your own question and even customize the poll choices.

After you‚Äôve shared your poll, your friends and followers can immediately start voting and see real-time results. Once someone has voted on your poll, they‚Äôll see which choice is in the lead at any given moment. And if they watch your story again later, they‚Äôll see the latest results.

To see your own poll results, swipe up to open the viewers list for that part of your story. Not only will you see how many votes each option received, but you‚Äôll also see who voted and what option they chose. That way, you‚Äôll be able to compare votes from the friends and followers whose opinions you trust most. And just like your story, your poll and its results will disappear after 24 hours.

Today, we‚Äôre announcing new tools and programs to keep Instagram a safe and positive place for self-expression. Since the beginning, we‚Äôve tried to make Instagram a welcoming place for everyone. Our community has grown to 800 million, with 500 million using it every day. It‚Äôs more important than ever to strengthen our commitment to safety and kindness.

Comment Controls

Over time, we‚Äôve launched a number of tools to help you manage the comments experience, and today we‚Äôre introducing more. Starting today, if your account is public, you‚Äôll see a new way to choose who can comment on your posts ‚Äî from everyone to just groups of people, like people you follow or your followers. Also, whether your account is public or private, you‚Äôll be able to block other accounts from commenting on your posts. In June, we launched a filter to block certain offensive comments in English, today we are expanding this filter to Arabic, French, German and Portuguese. The filter will improve over time, enabling the community‚Äôs experience of sharing to improve as well. 
  
Anonymous Reporting for Live Video

We‚Äôre continuing to provide mental health resources to you when you need them most. If you see someone going through a difficult time or in need of support during a live broadcast, you can report it anonymously. The person will see a message offering help with options to talk to a helpline, reach out to a friend or get other tips and support. We have teams working 24 hours a day, seven days a week, around the world to respond.

Kindness Walls and Stickers

Over the next few months, we‚Äôre turning walls in cities around the world into colorful murals inspiring #KindComments. Visit a wall, take a photo or video and share a #KindComment to make someone‚Äôs day. You can also participate by using a new kindness-themed heart-shaped sticker. Both the murals and stickers are created by artists from the global community. 

We feel as strongly about creating a safe and welcoming environment today as we did when our community was just getting started. To learn more about these tools and others, visit Instagram-Together.com. Thank you for being on this journey with us, and for taking care of each other. 

Kevin Systrom
Co-Founder & CEO

Today, we‚Äôre introducing two comment filters to help keep Instagram a safe place for self-expression: an offensive comments filter and a spam filter. These tools are the next step in our commitment to foster kind, inclusive communities on Instagram. 

Many of you have told us that toxic comments discourage you from enjoying Instagram and expressing yourself freely. To help, we‚Äôve developed a filter that will block certain offensive comments on posts and in live video. You can turn this filter off in the ‚Äú...‚Äù settings menu from the profile and scroll to tap ‚ÄúComments.‚Äù  We‚Äôll launch this in English first, but will offer it in more languages over time. The spam filter removes any obvious spam in comments written in English, Spanish, Portuguese, Arabic, French, German, Russian, Japanese and Chinese.

These filters are powered by machine learning, trained by our team to recognize certain types of offensive and spammy comments so you never have to see them. They will improve over time, enabling the community‚Äôs experience to improve as well. 

Our work is far from finished and perfect, but I hope we‚Äôre helping you feel safer and more welcome on Instagram.

Kevin Systrom 
CEO & Co-founder

Weekend Hashtag Project: #WHPfriendship

This weekend, the goal is to take photos and videos that capture the many aspects of friendship. Here are a few tips to get you started:

Consider the different ways that friendship can be represented ‚Äî not just through photos of friends themselves, but how relationships manifest in objects and actions. Take a photo of a thoughtful gift you were given, or a Hyperlapse of a helpful friend painting your kitchen with you. 

Show friends coming together, from gathering around the dinner table for a shared meal to a pickup soccer game. 

Keep an eye out for surprising or unlikely friendships: a dog and a cat snoozing together in a sunspot, a vine reaching out for a neighboring tree or a child embracing her new toy.

For some, the world goes to sleep at night. For others, it comes alive. This weekend, the goal is to capture both sides of that spectrum: the bright energy and the quiet rest.

Here are some tips to get you started:

Whether it‚Äôs calming down or speeding up, notice how the energy shifts. Document your family settling in for dinner or take a Boomerang of your friends hitting the town.

Look beyond your immediate circle ‚Äî how do other people react to the shift from day to night? Take a portrait of a server heading to work or a video of downtown streets emptying as office workers head home.

Weekend Hashtag Project: #WHPnaturalbeauty

Our planet is a timeless source of discovery, wonder and inspiration. This weekend, let‚Äôs celebrate Earth‚Äôs beauty. 

Here are a few tips to get you started:

Spend time in a majestic landscape. Mountains, beaches, plains, forests ‚Äî our land is diverse and grand, and it would take lifetimes to experience it all. How much can you capture within the frame of one photograph or video? Look for action and movement within the larger scene.

Focus on the smaller details. Our planet may be vast, but there are millions of tiny, beautiful moments playing out in front of us every day: a blooming flower pushing through the cracks in the sidewalk, a trickle of water feeding a small pool in the forest or a tree swaying gently in the breeze. 

Keep an eye out for how nature weaves its way into man-made scenes. City and country alike have their own elements of natural beauty.

Starting this week, you can save posts into private collections. Tap and hold the bookmark icon underneath any post to save it directly to a collection. You can create and name a new collection when you save a post, or you can add it to one you‚Äôve already created. You can also create a collection out of your existing saved posts. Tap the plus icon in the top right corner, give your collection a name and select the saved posts you‚Äôd like to add. 

You can find your collections on the saved posts tab on your profile. Just like all saved posts, your collections are private ‚Äî only you can see them. Since we introduced the ability to save posts last December, 46 percent of Instagrammers have saved at least one post. The goal this weekend is to make photos and videos documenting your creative process ‚Äî the why, the when and even the deeper question of how. San Francisco-based architect Dan Hogman (instagram.com/danhogman) tackles these questions during his sketching work: ‚ÄúArchitecture brings a sense of stability and timelessness,‚Äù he says. ‚ÄúBefore you get into the discussion on what it means or how it functions, a basic question is always current ‚Äî how to represent it? How to capture the essence in just a few strokes, whether it‚Äôs a single structure or a citywide scene,‚Äù says Dan, who makes daily drawings of settings and buildings that inspire him.

Here‚Äôs how to get started on your own submission this weekend: 

Document what happens when you sit down at the literal (or figurative) drawing board. When you put pen to paper ‚Äî or brush to canvas ‚Äî show what emerges, and how. 

Try exploring beyond what you might consider a typical creative process. How does a child line up her crayons? A bike repairman lay out his tools? Take note of the not-so-obvious creativity happening around you.

Experiment with different ways of capturing a creative process ‚Äî like a Hyperlapse of a mural coming to life or a Boomerang of an artist at work in her studio.

Last September, we made a commitment to the community to keep Instagram a safe place for everyone. This year we will continue to act on that commitment and also focus on fostering kindness within our community.

The first step is to celebrate the kindness our community is already known for. On March 25 and 26, Instagrammers will come together for the kindness-themed Worldwide InstaMeet 15. Join an InstaMeet near you ‚Äî or spread kindness by leaving an encouraging comment, giving an inspiring person a like or sharing a message of support with a friend.

As part of our goal to build a safe environment, we also have some updates to announce. Soon you may notice a screen over sensitive photos and videos when you scroll through your feed or visit a profile. While these posts don‚Äôt violate our guidelines, someone in the community has reported them and our review team has confirmed they are sensitive. This change means you are less likely to have surprising or unwanted experiences in the app. If you‚Äôd like to see a post that is covered with a screen, simply tap to reveal the photo or video. 

Our teams are focused on making Instagram a kind, welcoming place for everyone, and we‚Äôre just getting started.

Kevin Systrom
Co-founder & CEO

Now you can send disappearing photos and videos directly to groups and individual friends in a spontaneous, pressure-free way. Swipe right into the camera to take a photo or video, then tap the arrow to send it privately. You can choose a group or create one in just a few taps ‚Äî and you can also send to individual friends at the same time. Send anything you want, from inside jokes to your worst selfies. Unlike other messages in Direct, these photos and videos disappear from your friends‚Äô inboxes after they have seen them. And you‚Äôll see if they replayed it or took a screenshot.

To open your inbox, tap the new paper airplane icon at the top right corner of your feed or swipe left. You‚Äôll see disappearing photos and videos in a bar at the top. Tap the ones with blue rings to see what your friends sent you. In a group, you can see everyone‚Äôs responses ‚Äî and who else has seen them ‚Äî in a slideshow format. Then when you‚Äôre done, just tap their faded profile photo to send a quick response.

Disappearing photos and videos in Instagram Direct will start rolling out globally today.

To learn more about disappearing photos and videos in Instagram Direct, check out the Instagram Help Center: https://help.instagram.com/1750528395229662

The goal of this weekend‚Äôs hashtag project is to photograph the places you or a fellow artist go to be creative. The project takes inspiration from London-based artist and guest curator Helen Downie (instagram.com/unskilledworker), best known for her fashion-inspired portraits and paintings.

Here are Helen‚Äôs tips to get started:

Show off your unique studio space. ‚ÄúConcentrate on how important it is to have your own area ‚Äî outside, inside, wherever, somewhere where you can just be,‚Äù says Helen. ‚ÄúI think that everybody needs that.‚Äù

Photograph artists working, focusing on how different locations inspire people differently. ‚ÄúI sit in one chair to sketch. And then I go upstairs to a very small room to paint. And it‚Äôs always the same,‚Äù Helen says. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs just habit.‚Äù

Experiment with Hyperlapse and Boomerang to capture the artistic process, whether a painting coming to life or behind the scenes of a photo shoot in video form.

When Mike and I first created Instagram, we wanted it to be a welcoming community where people could share their lives. Images have the ability to inspire and bring out the best in us, whether they are funny, sad or beautiful. Over the past five years, I‚Äôve watched in wonder as this community has grown to 500 million, with stories from every corner of the world. With this growth, we want to work diligently to maintain what has kept Instagram positive and safe, especially in the comments on your photos and videos.

The beauty of the Instagram community is the diversity of its members. All different types of people ‚Äî from diverse backgrounds, races, genders, sexual orientations, abilities and more ‚Äî call Instagram home, but sometimes the comments on their posts can be unkind. To empower each individual, we need to promote a culture where everyone feels safe to be themselves without criticism or harassment. It‚Äôs not only my personal wish to do this, I believe it‚Äôs also our responsibility as a company. So, today, we‚Äôre taking the next step to ensure Instagram remains a positive place to express yourself.

The first feature we‚Äôre introducing is a keyword moderation tool that anyone can use. Now, when you tap the gear icon on your profile, you‚Äôll find a new Comments tool. This feature lets you list words you consider offensive or inappropriate. Comments containing these words will be hidden from your posts. You can choose your own list of words or use default words we‚Äôve provided. This is in addition to the tools we‚Äôve already developed such as swiping to delete comments, reporting inappropriate comments and blocking accounts.

We know tools aren‚Äôt the only solution for this complex problem, but together we can work toward keeping Instagram a safe place for self-expression. My commitment to you is that we will keep building features that safeguard the community and maintain what makes Instagram a positive and creative place for everyone.

To learn more about comments on Instagram, check out the Instagram Help Center: https://help.instagram.com/700284123459336

Kevin Systrom
CEO & Co-founder, Instagram

Weekend Hashtag Project: #WHPfriendshipis

International Day of Friendship is on July 30, and to celebrate, this weekend‚Äôs goal is to make photos and videos that capture every aspect of friendship ‚Äî like this one by @bonosurfdog. Here‚Äôs how to get started:
 
Grab a friend or a group and take a fun selfie that shows what it‚Äôs like when you spend time together. Try using Boomerang to add motion.
 
A horse who hangs with a duck? A puppy cuddle puddle? Share a photo of your pets or an animal odd couple.
 
Find letters from pen pals, care packages, friendship bracelets and any other tokens you have that mean friendship to you. 

PROJECT RULES: Please add the #WHPfriendshipis hashtag only to videos taken over this weekend and only submit your own visuals to the project. If you include music in your video submissions, please only use music to which you own the rights. Any tagged photo or video taken over the weekend is eligible to be featured next week.

Weekend Hashtag Project: #WHPilluminate
 
The goal this weekend is to make videos of interesting sources of light at night. Here‚Äôs how to get started:
 
Attend a fireworks show, concert or another event with large displays of moving or colorful lights. Try turning off your flash when you shoot to highlight the contrast between light and dark areas in your videos.
 
Try experimenting with a portable light source ‚Äî like a sparkler, glow stick or flashlight ‚Äî to create an interesting pattern for your video by moving the lights around in your frame.
 
Rather than shooting video of your light sources directly, try also looking around for subjects or areas the light is hitting in a striking way, like the flickering glow of a campfire on a friend‚Äôs face.
 
PROJECT RULES: Please add the #WHPilluminate hashtag only to photos and videos taken over this weekend and only submit your own visuals to the project. If you include music in your video submissions, please only use music to which you own the rights. Any tagged photo or video taken over the weekend is eligible to be featured next week.

Today we‚Äôre introducing a new look. You‚Äôll see an updated icon and app design for Instagram. Inspired by the previous app icon, the new one represents a simpler camera and the rainbow lives on in gradient form. You‚Äôll also see updated icons for our other creative apps: Layout, Boomerang and Hyperlapse.

We‚Äôve made improvements to how the Instagram app looks on the inside as well. The simpler design puts more focus on your photos and videos without changing how you navigate the app. 

The Instagram community has evolved over the past five years from a place to share filtered photos to so much more ‚Äî a global community of interests sharing more than 80 million photos and videos every day. Our updated look reflects how vibrant and diverse your storytelling has become.

Weekend Hashtag Project: #WHPpatterns

The goal this weekend is to look for patterns in your surroundings, both naturally occurring and man-made. Here‚Äôs how to get started:

Focus on highlighting the repetition of identifiable shapes in your scene.

Look for patterns large and small in scale ‚Äî whether zooming in close to the subtle lines on a flower petal or photographing the smokestacks of an industrial site from a distance.

Try using video to capture moving patterns ‚Äî like a line of ants marching in unison through your backyard.

Weekend Hashtag Project: #WHPsightsandsounds

The goal this weekend is to make videos with interesting ambient (or natural) sound, like this one by @hummingbirdsxoxo. Here‚Äôs how to get started:

Close your eyes and let your ears lead you to your subject.

Listen for sounds that set the mood ‚Äî like the upbeat squeak of sneakers sliding on a basketball court or the calming tones of church bells ringing in the morning.

Let the ambient noise guide the visual component of the video. For example, try panning your camera to slowly reveal the source of sound at the end.

Starting this week, you‚Äôll begin to see how many times people have watched a video on Instagram. 

Views are the most widely expected form of feedback on video. That‚Äôs why you‚Äôll begin to see view counts underneath videos where before you‚Äôd normally see likes. You‚Äôll be able to see likes by tapping ‚Äúviews.‚Äù

Since launching video two years ago and introducing Hyperlapse and Boomerang, you‚Äôve made video storytelling on Instagram take off. Whether sitting front row at Fashion Week or spending a day on the beach, nothing brings moments to life like video. Adding view counts is the first of many ways you‚Äôll see video on Instagram get better this year.

To learn more about video view counts on Instagram, visit the Instagram Help Center: https://help.instagram.com/551909181643223.

Video view counts are available as part of Instagram version 7.16 on iOS and Android.
